Age-related macular degeneration (AMD) is one of the leading causes of blindness 
worldwide with increasing prevalence owing to increased life expectancy. 
Intravitreal injections of antivascular endothelial growth factor agents are 
commonly used in exudative AMD and oral antioxidant medication for nonexudative 
AMD; however, many disorders mimic exudative and nonexudative AMD, and 
misdiagnosis can seriously affect the management of these patients. We summarize 
the demographics and clinical and imaging characteristics of each of the 
conditions that masquerade as AMD. As some of the conditions have features of 
AMD, a short update on the classical features of AMD is also included.

